Osteoporosis Risk Prediction – Project Report
📌 Objective
To develop a machine learning model that predicts the risk of osteoporosis in patients using historical health data, enabling early detection and personalized treatment planning.

🧠 Modeling Approach
Algorithm Used: Random Forest Classifier

Target Variable: Osteoporosis (Binary classification)

Features: Various patient health attributes (demographics, medical history, habits, etc.)

🔍 Data Preprocessing Steps
Loading Data: Imported from osteoporosis.csv.

Column Dropping: Removed the unique identifier Id as it has no predictive value.

Label Encoding: Converted categorical text columns into numerical values using LabelEncoder.

Train-Test Split: 80% training and 20% testing using train_test_split.

🧪 Model Training
Model: RandomForestClassifier with 100 estimators and random_state=42.

Training Data: Fit on the training set X_train and y_train.

📊 Evaluation Metrics
Accuracy: High accuracy achieved on test set.

Classification Report:

Precision

Recall

F1-score for each class

Confusion Matrix: Visual representation of predicted vs actual classes.

Feature Importance: Ranked features by their contribution to predictions.

📈 Key Visualizations
Confusion Matrix

Visualized using seaborn.heatmap

Helped evaluate true vs false positives and negatives.

Feature Importance Bar Plot

Showed the most influential features in osteoporosis prediction.